      "question": "What is the Kids-ID and how can it be obtained in Belgium?",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "The Kids-ID is an electronic identification document for Belgian children under 12 years old. It serves as both an identification and travel document, containing the child’s identity details, photo, and parents’ names. These details are visible on the card and stored on an electronic chip. While not mandatory in Belgium, the Kids-ID is required for travel abroad in certain cases."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "### Features of the Kids-ID\n- Valid in most European countries and some non-European countries.\n- Required in countries where adults can travel with only an ID card instead of a passport.\n- Includes the ‘Hallo Ouders’ service, allowing emergency contact with parents or guardians.\n- Children aged six and above can use the card for safe online identification and communication, but not for signing online documents."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "### Conditions\nTo apply for a Kids-ID, the following conditions must be met:\n- The applicant must have parental authority over the child.\n- Both the parent and child must be present during the application.\n\n**Photo Requirements:**\n- Some municipalities can take a photo during the application process. Check with your local authority beforehand.\n- If providing your own photo, it must be no older than six months and meet International Civil Aviation Organization standards."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "### Validity\n- A Kids-ID is valid for three years and remains valid even after the child turns 12.\n- At age 12, a child will receive an invitation to apply for an electronic ID card (eID) three months before the Kids-ID expires.\n- Moving to a new address does not require replacing the Kids-ID; the address on the chip can be updated by the municipality."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "### Procedure\n**Applying for a Kids-ID:**\n- Applications are made at the municipality where the child is registered.\n- The process takes 2–3 weeks; apply at least one month before traveling to avoid delays.\n- In case of theft, report it to the local police and inform your municipality. Stolen IDs are invalid even if recovered.\n\n**Collecting the Kids-ID:**\n- Codes for activation (PUK, PIN, and contact codes for the ‘Hallo Ouders’ service) are sent by mail.\n- Bring the codes when collecting the Kids-ID; the child does not need to be present for code activation."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "### Kids-ID for Belgian Children Abroad\nBelgian children under 12 residing abroad can apply for a Kids-ID at their local consulate. Processing times are longer for consular applications. Since June 21, 2021, Belgian municipalities can also handle Kids-ID applications for children registered in a consular population register, but only through a fast-track procedure."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "### Required Documents\n**For the Application:**\n- Electronic ID (eID) of the parent applying.\n- A recent color passport photo of the child (if the municipality does not take photos).\n\n**For Collecting the Kids-ID:**\n- The letter containing the PIN and PUK codes.\n- The previous Kids-ID (if applicable)."
        },
