  "question": "How can adults apply for Belgian nationality through the national declaration procedure?",
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Adults seeking to acquire or reclaim Belgian nationality can do so through the standard national declaration procedure. There are different categories of national declarations, depending on individual circumstances. In exceptional cases, naturalization may be an option, but it is rarely granted."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Eligibility\n- The national declaration procedure is open to adults wishing to acquire or reclaim Belgian nationality.\n- Specific conditions vary based on individual situations. For details on eligibility requirements, refer to the pages 'Which adults can become Belgian?' and 'Reclaiming Belgian nationality.'"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Steps in the Procedure\n**1. Pay the Registration Fee:**\n- A registration fee of €150 must be paid before submitting the declaration. This fee is waived for those reclaiming nationality.\n- Payment methods:\n  - Online via [MyMinfin](https://www.myminfin.be/).\n  - At the competent office of Legal Certainty (Rechtszekerheid).\n- Include proof of payment with your application. Applications without this proof are not processed.\n\n**2. Submit the Declaration and Required Documents:**\n- File the declaration at the civil registry of your municipality. For those abroad, it can be filed at a Belgian consular post.\n- The declaration must include the statement: \"I declare my desire to become a Belgian citizen and to respect the Constitution, the laws of the Belgian people, and the Convention for the Protection of Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms.\"\n- Provide all required documents. These are listed based on individual profiles on the relevant web pages.\n\n**3. Document Consistency:**\n- Ensure the spelling of your name and date of birth matches across all submitted documents and registries. Inconsistencies will result in indefinite suspension of the application until resolved.\n\n**4. Review by Civil Registry:**\n- The civil registry will review the completeness of your file within 30 days of submission. If incomplete, you are given two months to rectify the application.\n\n**5. Receive an Acknowledgment Receipt:**\n- If the application is complete, a receipt is issued within 35 working days or 15 working days after completing missing documents."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Review by Authorities\n- The civil registry forwards the file to:\n  - The public prosecutor's office.\n  - The Immigration Office.\n  - State Security.\n- The prosecutor provides a binding opinion within four months. If no opinion is given, the application is deemed approved."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Decision\n- **Positive Decision:**\n  - The civil registry records the declaration in the National Register, and you become Belgian from the date of registration.\n- **Negative Decision:**\n  - You are notified of the rejection and the reasons.\n  - Rejections can be appealed through the administrative courts."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "### Costs\n- **Registration Fee:** €150.\n- **Additional Fees:**\n  - Municipal taxes (varies by municipality).\n  - Court fees for appeals (€100).\n  - Legalization and translation of foreign documents not in Dutch, French, or German."
    },
    {
      "type": "source",
      "url": "https://www.vreemdelingenrecht.be/nationaliteit/procedures-belgische-nationaliteit/procedure-nationaliteitsverklaring"
    }
